# The What & The Why
I am making this website as a fast way to brush dust off my coding skills for my next trimester since I did not have any coding classes in this one.
As I approach the end of the term, I realise that I have not coded over the holidays either (too preoccupied with my side hustle). 
I decided that the best way to get back into things would be to just create something. Something simple, fast and deliverable. With that criteria, a personal website just made the most sense to me.

So what is this? This will be a site for me to showcase anything and everything. My personal thoughts, projects and more. My priorities are on keeping things clean, fast and easy to navigate.

# What Now?
This blog in specific will detail the process of engineering this site. Previously, I would not have detailed this, but I've come to realise that sometimes, when it comes to career aspects,
they don't just want to see what you have. They want to know how you made it, what processes you went through, what hardships you overcame, and how. Unrelated thought: This is reminiscent to how I remember 
Jensen Huang talking about how the best skill to have is grit. IDK.

# 14 April 26
## Side track
Today I started everything, FULL Disclosure, I do use AI to assist in making this site. Previously I did not use AI at all, and honestly thought it would just degrade my code quality, but after
seeing things online about AI workflows, cybersecurity and more, I started thinking I might need to learn how to effectively use AI. The tipping point came to me when I found out actual corporate jobs mandate its use.
I learned that TikTok interns are just now required to use AI for at least 20% of their code, and at CommBank interns use Agentic AI for most of their workflow. It was after hearing this that I realised, if I don't start now,
I will genuinely not know how to properly use AI should I need. By this I mean, not just typing a simple prompt into GPT, but actually getting quality information or work out of it. Making automated systems like OpenClaw and such is 
now something I want to learn to enhance my own productivity. So, while making and updating this site, I am trying to properly learn how to use AI properly and not just make it give out sh*tty code. And make this website as fast as possible.

## Back to Progress
what I've done:
- bulk of the basics down, design is done and site is up and working
- done resume page (file is missing currenlty because I don't want my data stolen)
- made blogs page dynamic so all I do is add my blog .md file in a folder and it should work fine
- put some example blogs in
I've gotten most of the Next.js components working, as well as the basic template files and hosting on Vercel. 
Simple problems and how I solved them:
- file not being found -> checked npm modules, and file path, refactored filepath to a const so that I can change the resume easily in the future. Checked multiple previews and the vscode one was bugged.
- blogs page not knowing how to work it out -> found out I had to add extra components in the [slug] and created a posts folder.
    - this version was reliant on me manually editing everything -> wanted it to be dynamic so changed it so that every future md file just needs some frontmatter and then can be dropped in the folder easily.
    - realised that putting blog sections on top of each other meant that you can't see the bottom categories -> created categories to sort the blogs and made a Buttons
    - -> same as above but for time and date.


